HB 2344 Aug 8: Unusual Southerly Position of Ice. Capt. E. Bjorndahl of the Norwegian motor ship Beaulieu, reports that on June 2, 1934, at 0950 a piece of ice 20' long, 8' wide, & showing 3' out of water, was passed 2 ship lengths off, & scattered in a northwest direction from the main piece were several small ice lumps. The temperature of the sea & air at 1000 was 75F & 77W, respectively. The captain further states that this ice was observed by his three officers as well as himself.
